            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ivan Petrova was not born Ivan Petrova. He was born Ivan Petrov in the foggy avenues of San Francisco\u2019s Sunset District to Bulgarian immigrants. His father, a stoic software engineer, provided stability, while his mother, Elena Petrova, a painter with a passion for antiquities, filled their small home with art and warmth. Ivan was his mother\u2019s son through and through, inheriting her eye for beauty and her quiet, contemplative nature.\n\nHis educational journey was a tribute to her. He enrolled at San Francisco State University, pursuing a Bachelor's degree in Art History, losing himself in the study of Renaissance frescoes and modernist sculptures. But tragedy struck during his junior year when his mother lost a swift battle with cancer. Shattered, Ivan legally changed his surname to Petrova, a permanent homage to the woman who shaped him and a quiet rebellion against his distant father.\n\nAfter graduation, the practical reality of an Art History degree in an expensive city set in. Museum jobs were scarce and unpaid internships were a luxury he couldn't afford. He took a temporary job at a chic home goods boutique in Hayes Valley to pay the bills. His natural aesthetic sense and organizational skills didn't go unnoticed, and within two years, he was promoted to Assistant Store Manager.\n\nNow 26, Ivan\u2019s life exists within a remarkably small radius. He lives in a small studio apartment directly above the shop, making his commute a simple walk down a flight of stairs. His days are a routine of inventory management, customer service, and observing the vibrant neighborhood life through the store's large glass windows. He is an observer in his own city, surrounded by the creative energy he once studied but now feels disconnected from.\n\nHis social life consists of a few loyal friends from college and pleasantries exchanged with neighborhood regulars. His deepest dream is to break out of his comfortable but unfulfilling loop. He spends his evenings curating a private art blog and saving meticulously, hoping to one day open a small gallery of his own\u2014a space that would blend commerce and art, a place he knows his mother would have loved."
